President Donald Trump and President Moon Jae-in of South Korea met in New York to discuss the threat posed by North Korea's nuclear and missile programs. They condemned North Korea's continued provocations, including its recent nuclear test and missile launches. The leaders emphasized the importance of faithfully implementing UN Security Council Resolutions 2371 and 2375. They agreed that maximum pressure and sanctions on North Korea are necessary to deter its threatening actions and work towards denuclearization. Both leaders reaffirmed their joint goal of achieving the complete, verifiable, and irreversible denuclearization of North Korea through peaceful means. They also emphasized the need to maintain military superiority over North Korea and committed to strengthening their defense posture. The deployment of U.S. strategic assets in and around South Korea on a rotational basis will be enhanced. The leaders pledged to continue close consultation when President Trump visits Seoul in November.